social_posts.post_text: Finally sharing a photo of the overhaul I gave the entryway nook in my front hallway. I mostly finished this up a couple months ago but I am allll about slow renovations these days 🙃 Swipe to see Ruby matching the space perfectly while staring at our mailman with deep love ♥️ And swipe again to see how far this space has come and how very much I’ve figured out and leaned into my personal style. #cohnewenglandcolonial #beforeandafter #cljxloloi #cljsquad

I wanted to show you how the little wallpapered entry nook connects to the rest of the entry hall 🖤🤍 You can also see the other changes made here…new wall color (BM Deserted Island) and trim color (BM Truffle at 50%). I’ve painted A LOT of walls but I’m still amazed at how paint can completely transform a room! Swipe to see the before☝🏼#cohnewenglandcolonial #BenjaminMoore #SeeTheLove

Want to know one of my greatest flaws when it comes to projects around here? I finish things just enough, to like 80%, and then move on and soon forget about the rest. So here we are in my dining room. I installed a chair rail, wallpapered above, painted below, painted the bookshelves, and made curtains a few years ago. I have six things left to do to take the room to 100% and I’m starting on it now! There’s going to be a lot of my purple worksuit around here over the next couple weeks 💜

I went to the danger zone you guys…I painted the crown moulding in my dining room dark blue, right up next to the beige grass cloth wallpaper. But good news! It all worked out. Phew. And this many years overdue project is ✔️ off the list! Color is @benjaminmoore Midnight Blue. Power players in getting clean lines were my obsessive favorite @woosterbrushcompany Shortcut brush and, of course, @frogtape 🐸

A color story, courtesy of the front of my house. It’s funny…I went a little wild with color in my first house. A different paint color in every room, not much thought to how they flowed one into the next. It was a lot. The first thing I did when we bought this house 9 years ago was paint everything shades of white and grey. I felt like I needed a blank slate. But I slowly started feeling myself drawn back to some color, but with restraint this time. It started with the dining room, I wanted a dark color to contrast with the beige grasscloth wallpaper, and settled on a rich grey-navy. Then I felt like I wanted another rich color on all of the wainscoting in the living room, and landed on a deep muddy red. When I turned my attention to the entryway warm shades of beige and white just felt right in between the two spaces, so I went with neutrals. The back of my house - the kitchen and family room - are still shades of grey and white and I love them just as they are. But this flow here feels so good to me, like my house is becoming what it was meant to be. So cheesy I know, but I’ve had that thought multiple times lately, like, yesss, this is how it’s supposed to be 💙🖤🤍♥️ Paint is all @benjaminmoore Midnight Navy (dining room), Deserted Island (entry walls), Truffle at 50% (entry trim), Georgian Brick (living room). #cohnewenglandcolonial #benajminmoore #SeeTheLove

It seems I’m adding oranges 🍊 to all my salads these days, my body is craving Vitamin C I guess 🤷🏼‍♀️ Quickie how-to here on how to cut oranges perfect for topping salads, yogurts, whatever! You cut all the peel away and then use a sharp knife to cut between membranes to make little segments. It’s just prettier that way if you’re using them as a topping. These are Cara Cara oranges, have you tried them? They’re SO GOOD. Like an orange with a little bit of raspberry. Yum.

I’ve done a lot of wainscoting projects over the past 15 years and here are my top five tips for doing it quickly with professional results. No exaggeration, I did this whole wall in about five minutes once the wood was cut!

These are my four favorite salad dressings 🥗 that go with pretty much any salad or grain bowl I make. They take minutes to mix together and keep in the fridge for weeks. And homemade salad dressing just tastes SO MUCH BETTER than store bought. You can find links to the mini blender I have and love (MVP🥇of homemade dressing making) and the no leak, no rust, dishwasher safe mason jar lids that are a major upgrade to all of my glass jars, right here 👉🏼https://liketk.it/41WCi For all the recipes just put all ingredients in a mini blender and blend until smooth. Save this post to go back to it easily anytime!

CIDER MAPLE VINAIGRETTE - a basic vinaigrette that’s good with just about anything
2 oz cider vinegar
2 oz maple syrup
3 oz olive oil
2 tsp dijon mustard
1 small shallot, peeled
Salt and pepper to taste 

CILANTRO LIME VINAIGRETTE - great with Mexican flavors
2 oz lime juice
3 oz avocado oil
1 oz honey
1 small jalapeño, seeds and ribs removed
1/4 c cilantro
1 clove garlic
Salt and pepper to taste

SESAME GINGER VINAIGRETTE - perfect dressing for Asian salads and bowls
2 oz rice vinegar
2 oz sunflower or avocado oil
1 oz sesame oil
1 tsp soy sauce
2 tsp tahini
1 tsp honey
1 clove garlic
1 tbsp ginger

GREEN GODDESS RANCH - you might want to eat this one with a spoon
1/3 c whole milk plain yogurt
1 c mayonnaise
1 small shallot, peeled
1/4 c each of fresh basil, cilantro, parsley, and dill
1 1/2 tbsp red wine vinegar
1 tbsp Franks hot sauce
1 tsp salt
1 tsp pepper

These were my six favorite fabric samples out of the ones I ordered for my dining room curtains. I’m down to the middle right and bottom right.
